This approach first checks the type of the input data `x`. If `x` is already a unicode string, it returns immediately. Otherwise, it ensures that any byte-based objects are first converted into the standard `bytes` format before decoding them into a string using your defined default encoding.

```python
def fromBytes(x):
    '''
    x-->unicode string | bytearray | bytes
    Returns-->unicode string, with encoding=latin1
    '''
    if isinstance(x, unicode):
        return x
    if isinstance(x, bytearray):
        x = bytes(x)
    elif isinstance(x, bytes):
        pass
    else:
        return x  # unchanged (int etc)
    return decode(x, DEF_ENCODING)
```

This function handles various types gracefully but relies on external constants (`DEF_ENCODING`) for the final transformation. If an unexpected data type is passed, it simply returns that object without modification.
